I"	<p>I received a tear-off Japanese calendar as a gift. Aside from horological symbols and other arcana, each day has a short saying at the bottom. I’ve started translating these as reading practice.</p>

<p>I haven’t studied Japanese long and some of them are quite obtuse - corrections are welcome.</p>

<h2 id="山椒は小粒でもぴりりと辛い１月１６日">山椒は小粒でもぴりりと辛い・１月１６日</h2>
<p><em>sanshou wa kutsubu demo piriri to karai</em><br />
Japanese pepper may be small, but it packs a punch.</p>

<h2 id="無病は一生の極楽１月２０日">無病は一生の極楽・１月２０日</h2>
<p>mubyou wa isshou no gokuraku<br />
Good health is a life in Paradise.</p>

<p><em>極楽 is the name of a Buddhist realm, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sukhavati">Sukhavati</a>.</em></p>

<h2 id="知る者ものは言わず言う者は知らず１月２１日">知る者ものは言わず言う者は知らず・１月２１日</h2>
<p><em>shirumono wa iwazu iumono wa shirazu</em><br />
Those who know do not say, those who say do not know.</p>

<h2 id="親しき仲にも礼儀有り１月２２日">親しき仲にも礼儀有り・１月２２日</h2>
<p><em>shitashiki naka ni mo reigi ari</em><br />
Good manners between good friends.</p>

<h2 id="沈む瀬あれば浮かぶ瀬あり１月２３日">沈む瀬あれば浮かぶ瀬あり・１月２３日</h2>
<p><em>shizumu se areba ukabu se ari</em><br />
If there’s downs, there’s ups.</p>

<p><em>How to translate this more literally… it’s about sinking waters and floating waters?</em></p>

<h2 id="石の上にも三年１月２４日">石の上にも三年・１月２４日</h2>
<p><em>ishi no ue ni mo san nen</em><br />
Three years on top of a stone</p>

<p><em>(…will warm it up.)</em></p>

<h2 id="聞くは一時の恥聞かぬは一生の恥１月２９日">聞くは一時の恥、聞かぬは一生の恥・１月２９日</h2>
<p><em>kiku wa hitotoki no haji, kikanu wa isshou no haji.</em><br />
Asking a question is embarassing for a moment, not asking for a lifetime.</p>

<h2 id="去る者は追わず１月３０日">去る者は追わず・１月３０日</h2>
<p><em>sarumono wa owazu</em><br />
Don’t chase after people.</p>

<p>起きて働く果報者・１月３１日</p>
